      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Tower Of Flowers</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Frances Anderton</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Anderton, Frances</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Photo of old oil tower in Beverly Hills that is painted with colorful flowers (Currents: Los Angeles)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>A joyful tower at 9865 Olympic Boulevard in Beverly Hills is the result of an ambitious art therapy project. The California Tower of Hope is actually a defunct oil drill that is clad in 220 polyvinyl-coated fiberglass panels painted in a flower design by 4,000 children in hospitals throughout California (helped by 35,000 California schoolchildren, who primed the panels). The project, soon to be illuminated at night, was conceived in 1995 by Ed Massey of Portraits of Hope, a public art and art therapy program.</p>
      </block>
